A material that melts and becomes liquid or viscous when heated. It solidifies upon cooling and re-melts when heated again. The cycle can be repeated many times without significantly changing the properties in either the solid or liquid state. The glass transition temperature, Tg, is a point that denotes the change from a crystalline or quasi-crystaline solid to a very viscous liquid liquid. In practice, for glassy thermoplastic materials this transition point may or may not not be present.